I'll use this Notes file to document what i learned about the software testing fundamentals, i'll use mostly my own
words to describe things the way I understanded them and sometimes i'll use the definitions found in the courses i
follow.


--------------------------// What is software testing? //--------------------------

 - The process of evaluating a software app to ensure that it meets the requirements, behaves as expected and does not
  have any other issues.
 - We detect issues and bugs before the application goes live, we validate the requirements and overall improve the
 quality of the software.
 - We create and execute test cases in order to verify everything. Test cases are like a validating list of if cases to
 describe what should be the output of an action (if input is xxxx then output should be yyy).

EX:  -> if i "click on Youtube icon" then the output should be "i'll be sent to the home page"
     -> if i "enter the wrong passord" then the output shold be "i receive an error telling me i entered the wrong
     password"

---------------------// Manual testing vs Automation testing //---------------------

 *Manual testing* 
   - Manual testing is a process where human testers create and execute test cases manually without the help of
   automated scripts.
   - Focused on the human observation of the interface and experience during the use of the software application
   - Is more susceptible to human error and takes more time to complete multiple tests.
   - If an application works as intended, it does not mean it is free of bugs or issues to be solved. Sometimes the
   application follows the test case properly and everything works as intended, but the UX is not desired by the
   application users. This can be reported and updated by the developers to improve the quality of the the user
   experience. This can only be detected by the manual tester during exploratory testing.

|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|                   PROS                     |                CONS                  |
|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Humans can catch more UI/UX issues         | Is more time consumming              |
| Better for exploratory testing             | More susceptible to human error      |
| No need for sperial tools or framework     | Not scalable to complex test suites  |
|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------| 


 *Automation testing*
   - Uses specialized test tools to automatically follow scripts in order to execute test cases
   - Uses those test tools to run repetitive tests faster and more consistent than an manual tester without the fear of
   human error.

|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|                         PROS                        |                               CONS                            |
|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Faster in executing multiple tests                  | Requires more effort to setup the tools and write scripts     |
| Human error is no longer an issue to worry about    | The scripts must be updated contantly as the software changes |
| Supports larger test suits and complex situations   | The scripts follow a specific path, without noticing other    |
| Better for CI/CD pipelines for continuous testing   | aesthetic issues that might be encountered                    |
|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|


------------------// What is Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) //------------------ 

 - Is the process a software application goes through during development
 
          |----------|         |----------|         |--------|
|-------> | Planning | ------> | Analysis | ------> | Design | --------|
|         |----------|         |----------|         |--------|         |    
|                                                                      |
|                                                                      |
|                 SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT LIFE CYCLE                      |
|                                                                      |
|                                                                      | 
|                           |-------------|                            |
|      |-------------|      |    Test     |      |----------------|    |
|----- | Maintanance | <--- |      &      | <--- | Implementation | <--|
       |-------------|      | Integration |      |----------------|
                            |-------------|

 - SDLC Methodologies: 

*Agile* 

 - An iterative approach to software development where requirements and solutions evolve through collaboration
 - Implmenting the app and the tests start to go at the same time as planning and the analysis comparing the intended
 results witht he test results

*Waterfall*

 - A linear, sequential approach where each phase of development must be completed before moving to the next.
 - There are fixed requirements from the start. 
 - Easier to manage for small projects with well designed features, but is not good for projects with changing
 requirements, resulting in increased cost for development.

 













































